That means you would have 
7.7 shares of $SBUX
0.28 shares of $AMZN 
2.1 shares of $AAPL 
3.1 shares of $FB

This gives you a greater level of protection should one of those stocks not pan out.

In this case it might work out for you 
b/c $AMZN had done well. But if you put 80% of your üí∞ in a cruise line or airline stock the story might be different.

That would mean you have: 

$73 in $SBUX
$2,042 in $AMZN 
$267 in $AAPL 
$175 in $FB

You have a total of $2,257...but 80% of your money is in Amazon which was down today. 

Instead of spreading the risk across each of the stocks, you've almost bet everything in this one company.

"How many shares should I buy?" 

This is a question I've gotten a lot lately and want to explain why the number of shares you have isn't as important as you think. 

Let's say you own 1 share of your favorite stocks: 
$SBUX 
$AMZN 
$AAPL
